```

As you can see, the two parameters screenWidth and screenHeight are not used.

Right now AndroidAudio:147 is like this:
AssetFileDescriptor descriptor = aHandle.assets.openFd(aHandle.path());
it would be nice to have an option where asset is null but the descriptor is set in a new constructor for AndroidFileHandle which would accept an AssetFileDescriptor and then line 147 would be replaced with this:
if(aHandle.assets == null)
    descriptor = aHandle.descriptor;

This would enable developers to use http://dnd-aac.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/Google%20Play%20Zip%20Library/src/com/android/vending/expansion/zipfile/ZipResourceFile.java
without having to extract the sound files into an another directory, basically doubling the resources.

I've stumbled across an error when wrapping the text of labels.  It's due to a floating point error in GlyphLayout, so is extremely sensitive to its input, but the following code should reproduce it:

```
public class FontWrapIssue extends ApplicationAdapter {

    private static final float GAME_WIDTH = 230.4f;

    private Stage stage;

    @Override
    public void create () {
        float gameScale = GAME_WIDTH / Gdx.graphics.getWidth();
        int gameHeight = (int) (Gdx.graphics.getHeight() * gameScale + 0.5);
        stage = new Stage(new FitViewport(GAME_WIDTH, gameHeight));
        Gdx.input.setInputProcessor(stage);
        resize(Gdx.graphics.getWidth(), Gdx.graphics.getHeight());
        FreeTypeFontGenerator generator = new FreeTypeFontGenerator(Gdx.files.internal("data/arial.ttf"));
        FreeTypeFontGenerator.FreeTypeFontParameter parameter = new FreeTypeFontGenerator.FreeTypeFontParameter();
        parameter.size = (int) (20 / gameScale + 0.5);
        BitmapFont font = generator.generateFont(parameter);
        font.getData().setScale(gameScale);
        Label.LabelStyle labelStyle = new Label.LabelStyle();
        labelStyle.font = font;
        labelStyle.fontColor = Color.WHITE;
        String text = "test with wHVVVl wHVVVl issue";
        Table table = new Table();
        table.setFillParent(true);
        addLabel(table, text, labelStyle);
        stage.addActor(table);
        table.debug();
    }

    private void addLabel(Table table, String text, Label.LabelStyle labelStyle) {
        Label label = new Label(text, labelStyle);
        label.setWrap(true);
        table.add(label).fillX().expandX().row();
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        stage.act(Gdx.graphics.getDeltaTime());
        stage.draw();
    }

    public static void main (String[] args) throws Exception {
        new LwjglApplication(new FontWrapIssue());
    }
}
```

Screenshot where you can see the text wrapping outside the Label's boundary:
![fontwrapissue](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1848870/7227694/01420e9a-e796-11e4-8cea-50c7f741d945.png)

The floating point error occurs when the glyphRun is wrapped (in version 1.5.6, `GlyphLayout.java` lines 287-288 and the loop at 297).  To work out the the width of the wrapped run, the code calculates backwards from the current position by subtracting the xAdvances of the glyphs that overshot the desired width (including any white space).  However, due to floating point rounding errors the result can occasionally be slightly smaller than the result of summing all the xAdvances of the glyphs leading up to the wrap point (i.e. we have `x + w1 + w2 + ...  - w1 - w2 - ...` giving a result different from x).

That error alone would just result in the text wrapping in the wrong place.  The reason the text of the `Label` goes outside its boundary is because the code in `Label.computeSize()` that calculates the bounds of the label always uses the actor's width as the targetWidth passed to `layout.setText()`, so it doesn't care about the error in the run length.  The code in `Label.layout()` however calculates the targetWidth based on the computed bounds, which will be fractionally too narrow in the case when this floating point error occurs.  IMHO, `Label.layout()` should always use a targetWidth that matches whatever `Label.computeSize()` uses (for wrapped text at least), so there is never a discrepancy.

![2015-04-20 11 18 43](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/12011951/7226214/56df01ba-e74f-11e4-9383-b3e66ec221c5.png)

