The current implementation of `Json` has a special handling for map-like datastructures. It tries to serialize `java.util.Map`, `com.badlogic.gdx.utils.ArrayMap` and `com.badlogic.gdx.utils.ObjectMap` in special ways.

As always with the libgdx collection framework, there are more classes that are not covered in a generic way (like `ObjectIntMap` for example). I guess that's a problem that cannot be solved though.

However, it's good that at least some standard classes are covered. On the other hand, they are serialized in a pretty weird way. It looks like the map entries are serialized as fields with "key=value". If I saw it right, it's possible to configure the value type serialization by setting the `elementType`. It's not possible though to change how the keys are serialized. The keys are just converted to a string as the fields name ([code](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/master/gdx/src/com/badlogic/gdx/utils/Json.java#L516)).

That works sometimes (in case there is a simple String representation, like for Enum, Integer, String itself etc). However they are also read back as Strings, since there is no way for Json to know which type is expected (because of type erasure).

A simple example:

```
ObjectMap<Integer, Integer> numbers = new ObjectMap<Integer, Integer>();
numbers.put(10, 5);
String jsonString = json.toJson(numbers);
System.out.println(jsonString);
numbers = json.fromJson(ObjectMap.class, jsonString);
System.out.println(numbers);
System.out.println(numbers.get(10));
```

Will result in this:

```
{10:{class:java.lang.Integer,value:5}}
{10=5}
null
```

That last `null` is unexpected. That's because in our `ObjectMap<Integer, Integer>`, we now have a _`String`_ key instead of `Integer`. Type erasure at work.

I'd suggest to change the current serialization to actually serialize the entries of the map as an array of entries instead of key=value fields.

[Here](http://pastebin.com/0h5yVNdU) is an implementation of a `ObjectMapSerializer` which makes use of that approach and is able to serialize and deserialize the maps correctly.

I think this is a much better way of doing it. If you agree, I'll try to make a PR for that.

Loading any PNG that is not RGBA results in corrupted Gdx2dPixmap data (see attached).

Code used to load the pixmap (and create the raw RGB file I used to make the attached .png):
        try {
          final FileHandle hfile = Preconditions.checkNotNull(getFileHandle(assetPath));
          byte[] bytes = hfile.readBytes();
          Gdx2DPixmap pm = new Gdx2DPixmap(bytes, 0, bytes.length, 0);
          // Note: if you inspect the DirectByteBuffer memory for pm.getPixels() at this point
          // you will notice that it has corrupted samples.
          File outFile = new File("particle_gdx2dpixmap.rgb");
          FileChannel out = new FileOutputStream(outFile, false).getChannel();
          out.write(pm.getPixels());
          out.close();
      }

The resulting pixmap has '255' values inserted every fourth byte, even though it's RGB and not RGBA.

